AB  - Purpose: To examine the association between preoperative anticholinergic medication use and postoperative delirium (POD) in elderly patients undergoing hip replacement. Methods: Case-control study nested within a cohort of 312 patients ≥70 years. POD was assessed using CAM-ICU. Anticholinergic burden was quantified using the Anticholinergic Cognitive Burden scale. Results: High anticholinergic burden (score ≥3) was associated with increased POD risk (adjusted OR 4.2, 95% CI 2.1-8.4). Each unit increase in anticholinergic burden increased POD risk by 38% (OR 1.38, 95% CI 1.15-1.66). Conclusion: Minimizing anticholinergic medications preoperatively may reduce POD risk.
